 4197:     """Input validation on an array, list, or similar.
 4198:     By default, the input is checked to be a non-empty 2D array containing
 4199:     only finite values. If the dtype of the array is object, attempt
 4200:     converting to float, raising on failure.
 4201: 
 4202:     Parameters
 4203:     ----------
 4204:     array : object
 4205:         Input object to check / convert.
 4206: 
 4207:     accept_sparse : str, bool or list/tuple of str, default=False
 4208:         String[s] representing allowed sparse matrix formats, such as 'csc',
 4209:         'csr', etc. If the input is sparse but not in the allowed format,
 4210:         it will be converted to the first listed format. True allows the input
 4211:         to be any format. False means that a sparse matrix input will
 4212:         raise an error.
 4213:     accept_large_sparse : bool, default=True
 4214:         If a CSR, CSC, COO or BSR sparse matrix is supplied and accepted by
 4215:         accept_sparse, accept_large_sparse=False will cause it to be accepted
 4216:         only if its indices are stored with a 32-bit dtype.
 4217: 
 4218:     dtype : 'numeric', type, list of type or None, default='numeric'
 4219:         Data type of result. If None, the dtype of the input is preserved.
 4220:         If "numeric", dtype is preserved unless array.dtype is object.
 4221:         If dtype is a list of types, conversion on the first type is only
 4222:         performed if the dtype of the input is not in the list.
 4223:     order : {'F', 'C'} or None, default=None
 4224:         Whether an array will be forced to be fortran or c-style.
 4225:         When order is None (default), then if copy=False, nothing is ensured
 4226:         about the memory layout of the output array; otherwise (copy=True)
 4227:         the memory layout of the returned array is kept as close as possible
 4228:         to the original array.
 4229:     copy : bool, default=False
 4230:         Whether a forced copy will be triggered. If copy=False, a copy might
 4231:         be triggered by a conversion.
 4232:     force_all_finite : bool or 'allow-nan', default=True
 4233:         Whether to raise an error on np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in array. The
 4234:         possibilities are:
 4235:         - True: Force all values of array to be finite.
 4236:         - False: accepts np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in array.
 4237:         - 'allow-nan': accepts only np.nan and pd.NA values in array. Values
 4238:           cannot be infinite.
 4239:           ``force_all_finite`` accepts the string ``'allow-nan'``.
 4240:            Accepts `pd.NA` and converts it into `np.nan`
 4241:     ensure_2d : bool, default=True
 4242:         Whether to raise a value error if array is not 2D.
 4243:     ensure_min_samples : int, default=1
 4244:         Make sure that the array has a minimum number of samples in its first
 4245:         axis (rows for a 2D array). Setting to 0 disables this check.
 4246:     ensure_min_features : int, default=1
 4247:         Make sure that the 2D array has some minimum number of features
 4248:         (columns). The default value of 1 rejects empty datasets.
 4249:         This check is only enforced when the input data has effectively 2
 4250:         dimensions or is originally 1D and ``ensure_2d`` is True. Setting to 0
 4251:         disables this check.
 4252:     estimator : str or estimator instance, default=None
 4253:         If passed, include the name of the estimator in warning messages.
 4254:     input_name : str, default=""
 4255:         The data name used to construct the error message. In particular
 4256:         if `input_name` is "X" and the data has NaN values and
 4257:         allow_nan is False, the error message will link to the imputer
 4258:         documentation.
 4259: 
 4260:     to_frame: bool, default=False
 4261:         Reconvert array back to pd.Series or pd.DataFrame if
 4262:         the original array is pd.Series or pd.DataFrame.
 4263: 
 4264:     Returns
 4265:     -------
 4266:     array_converted : object
 4267:         The converted and validated array.
 4268:     """

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5tools_9validator_148check_X_y, "Input validation for standard estimators.\n    Checks X and y for consistent length, enforces X to be 2D and y 1D. By\n    default, X is checked to be non-empty and containing only finite values.\n    Standard input checks are also applied to y, such as checking that y\n    does not have np.nan or np.inf targets. For multi-label y, set\n    multi_output=True to allow 2D and sparse y. If the dtype of X is\n    object, attempt converting to float, raising on failure.\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    X : {ndarray, list, sparse matrix}\n        Input data.\n    y : {ndarray, list, sparse matrix}\n        Labels.\n    accept_sparse : str, bool or list of str, default=False\n        String[s] representing allowed sparse matrix formats, such as 'csc',\n        'csr', etc. If the input is sparse but not in the allowed format,\n        it will be converted to the first listed format. True allows the input\n        to be any format. False means that a sparse matrix input will\n        raise an error.\n    accept_large_sparse : bool, default=True\n        If a CSR, CSC, COO or BSR sparse matrix is supplied and accepted by\n        accept_sparse, accept_large_sparse will cause it to be accepted only\n        if its indices are stored with a 32-bit dtype.\n    dtype : 'numeric', type, list of type or None, default='numeric'\n        Data type of result. If None, the dtype of the input is preserved.\n        If \"numeric\", dtype is preserved unless array.dtype is object.\n        If dtype is a list of types, conversion on the first type is only\n        performed if the dtype of the input is not in the list.\n    order : {'F', 'C'}, default=None\n        Whether an array will be forced to be fortran or c-style.\n    copy : bool, default=False\n        Whether a forced copy will be triggered. If copy=False, a copy might\n        be triggered by a conversion.\n    force_all_finite : bool or 'allow-nan', default=True\n        Whether to raise an error on np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA i""n X. This parameter\n        does not influence whether y can have np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA values.\n        The possibilities are:\n        - True: Force all values of X to be finite.\n        - False: accepts np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in X.\n        - 'allow-nan': accepts only np.nan or pd.NA values in X. Values cannot\n          be infinite.\n        .. versionadded:: 0.20\n           ``force_all_finite`` accepts the string ``'allow-nan'``.\n        .. versionchanged:: 0.23\n           Accepts `pd.NA` and converts it into `np.nan`\n    ensure_2d : bool, default=True\n        Whether to raise a value error if X is not 2D.\n    allow_nd : bool, default=False\n        Whether to allow X.ndim > 2.\n    multi_output : bool, default=False\n        Whether to allow 2D y (array or sparse matrix). If false, y will be\n        validated as a vector. y cannot have np.nan or np.inf values if\n        multi_output=True.\n    ensure_min_samples : int, default=1\n        Make sure that X has a minimum number of samples in its first\n        axis (rows for a 2D array).\n    ensure_min_features : int, default=1\n        Make sure that the 2D array has some minimum number of features\n        (columns). The default value of 1 rejects empty datasets.\n        This check is only enforced when X has effectively 2 dimensions or\n        is originally 1D and ``ensure_2d`` is True. Setting to 0 disables\n        this check.\n    y_numeric : bool, default=False\n        Whether to ensure that y has a numeric type. If dtype of y is object,\n        it is converted to float64. Should only be used for regression\n        algorithms.\n    estimator : str or estimator instance, default=None\n        If passed, include the name of the estimator in warning messages.\n        \n    Returns\n    -------\n    X_converted : object\n        The converted and validated X.\n    y_converted : object\n        The converted and validated y.\n    ");

 4508:     """Input validation for standard estimators.
 4509:     Checks X and y for consistent length, enforces X to be 2D and y 1D. By
 4510:     default, X is checked to be non-empty and containing only finite values.
 4511:     Standard input checks are also applied to y, such as checking that y
 4512:     does not have np.nan or np.inf targets. For multi-label y, set
 4513:     multi_output=True to allow 2D and sparse y. If the dtype of X is
 4514:     object, attempt converting to float, raising on failure.
 4515:     Parameters
 4516:     ----------
 4517:     X : {ndarray, list, sparse matrix}
 4518:         Input data.
 4519:     y : {ndarray, list, sparse matrix}
 4520:         Labels.
 4521:     accept_sparse : str, bool or list of str, default=False
 4522:         String[s] representing allowed sparse matrix formats, such as 'csc',
 4523:         'csr', etc. If the input is sparse but not in the allowed format,
 4524:         it will be converted to the first listed format. True allows the input
 4525:         to be any format. False means that a sparse matrix input will
 4526:         raise an error.
 4527:     accept_large_sparse : bool, default=True
 4528:         If a CSR, CSC, COO or BSR sparse matrix is supplied and accepted by
 4529:         accept_sparse, accept_large_sparse will cause it to be accepted only
 4530:         if its indices are stored with a 32-bit dtype.
 4531:     dtype : 'numeric', type, list of type or None, default='numeric'
 4532:         Data type of result. If None, the dtype of the input is preserved.
 4533:         If "numeric", dtype is preserved unless array.dtype is object.
 4534:         If dtype is a list of types, conversion on the first type is only
 4535:         performed if the dtype of the input is not in the list.
 4536:     order : {'F', 'C'}, default=None
 4537:         Whether an array will be forced to be fortran or c-style.
 4538:     copy : bool, default=False
 4539:         Whether a forced copy will be triggered. If copy=False, a copy might
 4540:         be triggered by a conversion.
 4541:     force_all_finite : bool or 'allow-nan', default=True
 4542:         Whether to raise an error on np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in X. This parameter
 4543:         does not influence whether y can have np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA values.
 4544:         The possibilities are:
 4545:         - True: Force all values of X to be finite.
 4546:         - False: accepts np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in X.
 4547:         - 'allow-nan': accepts only np.nan or pd.NA values in X. Values cannot
 4548:           be infinite.
 4549:         .. versionadded:: 0.20
 4550:            ``force_all_finite`` accepts the string ``'allow-nan'``.
 4551:         .. versionchanged:: 0.23
 4552:            Accepts `pd.NA` and converts it into `np.nan`
 4553:     ensure_2d : bool, default=True
 4554:         Whether to raise a value error if X is not 2D.
 4555:     allow_nd : bool, default=False
 4556:         Whether to allow X.ndim > 2.
 4557:     multi_output : bool, default=False
 4558:         Whether to allow 2D y (array or sparse matrix). If false, y will be
 4559:         validated as a vector. y cannot have np.nan or np.inf values if
 4560:         multi_output=True.
 4561:     ensure_min_samples : int, default=1
 4562:         Make sure that X has a minimum number of samples in its first
 4563:         axis (rows for a 2D array).
 4564:     ensure_min_features : int, default=1
 4565:         Make sure that the 2D array has some minimum number of features
 4566:         (columns). The default value of 1 rejects empty datasets.
 4567:         This check is only enforced when X has effectively 2 dimensions or
 4568:         is originally 1D and ``ensure_2d`` is True. Setting to 0 disables
 4569:         this check.
 4570:     y_numeric : bool, default=False
 4571:         Whether to ensure that y has a numeric type. If dtype of y is object,
 4572:         it is converted to float64. Should only be used for regression
 4573:         algorithms.
 4574:     estimator : str or estimator instance, default=None
 4575:         If passed, include the name of the estimator in warning messages.
 4576: 
 4577:     Returns
 4578:     -------
 4579:     X_converted : object

 4581:     y_converted : object

If the input is sparse but\n        not in the allowed format, it will be converted to the first listed\n        format. True allows the input to be any format. False means\n        that a sparse matrix input will raise an error.\n    dtype : str, type or None\n        Data type of result. If None, the dtype of the input is preserved.\n    copy : bool\n        Whether a forced copy will be triggered. If copy=False, a copy might\n        be triggered by a conversion.\n    force_all_finite : bool or 'allow-nan'\n        Whether to raise an error on np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in X. The\n        possibilities are:\n        - True: Force all values of X to be finite.\n        - False: accepts np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in X.\n        - 'allow-nan': accepts only np.nan and pd.NA values in X. Values cannot\n          be infinite.\n        .. versionadded:: 0.20\n           ``force_all_finite`` accepts the string ``'allow-nan'``.\n        .. versionchanged:: 0.23\n           Accepts `pd.NA` and converts it into `np.nan`\n    estimator_name : str, default=None\n        The estimator name, used to construct the error message.\n    input_name : str, default=\"\"\n        The data name used to construct the error message. In particular\n        if `input_name` is \"X\" and the data has NaN values and\n        allow_nan is False, the error message will link to the imputer\n        documentation.\n    Returns\n    -------\n    spmatrix_converted : sparse matrix.\n        Matrix that is ensured to have an allowed type.\n    ");

 5118:         String[s] representing allowed sparse matrix formats ('csc',
 5119:         'csr', 'coo', 'dok', 'bsr', 'lil', 'dia'). If the input is sparse but
 5120:         not in the allowed format, it will be converted to the first listed
 5121:         format. True allows the input to be any format. False means
 5122:         that a sparse matrix input will raise an error.
 5123:     dtype : str, type or None
 5124:         Data type of result. If None, the dtype of the input is preserved.
 5125:     copy : bool
 5126:         Whether a forced copy will be triggered. If copy=False, a copy might
 5127:         be triggered by a conversion.
 5128:     force_all_finite : bool or 'allow-nan'
 5129:         Whether to raise an error on np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in X. The
 5130:         possibilities are:
 5131:         - True: Force all values of X to be finite.
 5132:         - False: accepts np.inf, np.nan, pd.NA in X.
 5133:         - 'allow-nan': accepts only np.nan and pd.NA values in X. Values cannot
 5134:           be infinite.
 5135:         .. versionadded:: 0.20
 5136:            ``force_all_finite`` accepts the string ``'allow-nan'``.
 5137:         .. versionchanged:: 0.23

 5144:         allow_nan is False, the error message will link to the imputer
